data.content:
Here's how to test `DataFetcher` with modern MSTest, covering success, failure, timeout, and cancellation:

```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class DataFetcherTests
{
    private readonly TestContext _testContext;
    private readonly MockHttpMessageHandler _handler;
    private readonly DataFetcher _sut;

    public DataFetcherTests(TestContext testContext)
    {
        _testContext = testContext;
        _handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler();
        _sut = new DataFetcher(new HttpClient(_handler));
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public async Task FetchAsync_SuccessResponse_ReturnsContent()
    {
        _handler.Response = new HttpResponseMessage
        {
            StatusCode = HttpStatusCode.OK,
            Content = new StringContent("hello")
        };

        var result = await _sut.FetchAsync("https://example.com");

        Assert.AreEqual("hello", result);
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public async Task FetchAsync_NotFound_ThrowsHttpRequestException()
    {
        _handler.Response = new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.NotFound);

        await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<HttpRequestException>(
            async () => await _sut.FetchAsync("https://example.com"));
    }

    [TestMethod]
    [Timeout(3000)]
    public async Task FetchAsync_WithTimeout_CompletesInTime()
    {
        _handler.Response = new HttpResponseMessage
        {
            StatusCode = HttpStatusCode.OK,
            Content = new StringContent("fast")
        };

        // Pass TestContext.CancellationToken for cooperative timeout
        var result = await _sut.FetchAsync(
            "https://example.com", _testContext.CancellationToken);

        Assert.AreEqual("fast", result);
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public async Task FetchAsync_WhenCancelled_ThrowsOperationCanceled()
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        cts.Cancel(); // cancel immediately

        await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<TaskCanceledException>(
            async () => await _sut.FetchAsync("https://example.com", cts.Token));
    }
}
```

And the minimal test double for `HttpClient`:

```csharp
private sealed class MockHttpMessageHandler : HttpMessageHandler
{
    public HttpResponseMessage Response { get; set; } = new(HttpStatusCode.OK);

    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        cancellationToken.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        return Task.FromResult(Response);
    }
}
```

**Key patterns used:**

| Pattern | Why |
|---|---|
| Constructor init (not `[TestInitialize]`) | Enables `readonly` fields, satisfies nullability |
| `TestContext` via constructor injection | MSTest 3.6+ preferred approach |
| `TestContext.CancellationToken` with `[Timeout]` | Cooperative timeout — MSTest cancels the token when time expires |
| `Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<T>` | Replaces `[ExpectedException]`; lets you inspect the exception |
| `sealed` test class + handler | Performance and design clarity |
| Custom `HttpMessageHandler` | Avoids mocking framework; gives full control over responses |

The critical detail: **always flow `TestContext.CancellationToken`** into your async calls in timeout tests. Without it, `[Timeout]` has no way to cooperatively stop the method and must forcibly abort the thread.
